\section{Analysis of the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ absorption}    
\label{sec:highion}        

In this section we will discuss the properties of the high-ionization gas phase traced by the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ doublet. The Voigt profile decomposition of the detected {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:highion}. A minimum of 3 components are required for fitting both the doublet members adequately. Note that the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}~$\lambda$1037 is blended with the $\rm L5P1$ transition of {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}. The doublets are fitted simultaneously taking into account the contribution of the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ line. The fit parameters are summarized in Table~\ref{fig:highion}. As mentioned previously, {\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}}\ and {\mbox{N\,{\sc v}}}\ are not detected in this system. Formal 3$\sigma$ upper limits on column densities for these ions are also presented in the table.     



We run constant density {\sc cloudy} simulations under optically thin conditions with a stopping $N({\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}})$ of $10^{14}$~{cm$^{-2}$}\ and the extra-galactic UV background radiation at $z=0.42$ \citep[]{Haardt12} as the ionizing continuum. In Figure~\ref{fig:highion} we show the results of our photoionization model. In the top-left corner of the figure the variations of $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})/N({\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}})$ and $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})/N({\mbox{N\,{\sc v}}})$ ratios with density are shown. The observed lower limits on these ratios suggest $\log n_{\rm H}<-4.4$, provided the relative abundances of N, C, and O are solar. Under-abundance of C or N with respect of O would require even lower densities. From the bottom-left panel it is evident that the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ ionization fraction, $f_{{\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}}$, peaks at $\log n_{\rm H}\simeq-4.5$ and decreases for $\log n_{\rm H}>-5.0$. The {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ column density can be expressed as $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}) = f_{{\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}}~{\rm 10^{[O/H]}~(O/H)_{\odot}}~n_{\rm H}~L_{\rm los}$, where, $L_{\rm los}$ is the line of sight thickness of the absorbing gas. Using the maximum $f_{{\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}}$ value, i.e. at $n_{\rm H} = -4.5$, it is now possible to examine how $L_{\rm los}$ changes with metallicity, $\rm [O/H]$, of the absorber for a given $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})$. The corresponding plot, for the strongest {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ component with $\log N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})=14.34$, is shown in the right panel of Figure~\ref{fig:highion}. It is clear that a metallicity much lower than $1/10$ of solar (i.e. $\rm [O/H] = -1.0$) is not permitted as it requires unreasonably large ($>$Mpc) line of sight thickness. If the high ionization gas phase has a metallicity similar to the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ bearing gas phase (i.e. $\rm [O/H]=-0.26$) then the deduced $L_{\rm los}$ is 28~kpc. Lower $f_{{\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}}$ values at lower densities, since higher densities are forbidden, would require slightly higher values of $L_{\rm los}$. But the thickness could be smaller for higher metallicities. Therefore, the detected {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ can have a reasonable solution under photoionization equilibrium provided $\rm [O/H] > -1.0$. The only caveat here is that we assumed that the $f_{{\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}}$ is independent of metallicity, which is not strictly true for very high metallicities (e.g. ${\rm [O/H]}>0.5$). Nonetheless, the effect is small and the cloud size becomes unreasonably large only at lower metallicities.   



Finally, we note that if the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ is in collisional ionization equilibrium \citep[]{Gnat07} then the lower limits on the $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})/N({\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}})$ and $N({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})/N({\mbox{N\,{\sc v}}})$ ratios require a gas temperature of $\log T > 5.4$ which is consistent with the maximum allowed temperatures evaluated from $b({\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}})$ in Table~\ref{tab:highion}.        





