\section{Absorption Analysis} 
\label{sec:absana}

\subsection{Description of the Absorber}  
\label{subsec:des}  

In Figure~\ref{fig:vplot} we display the absorption profiles of {Ly$\alpha$}\ and different metal lines arising from the {$z_{\rm abs}$}~$=$~0.4298 absorber. The {Ly$\alpha$}\ absorption clearly shows a damping wing. Strong, saturated absorption lines from {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda\lambda$~2796,2803 doublets are detected in the high resolution Keck spectrum. The very weak component at $v\sim+$90~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ is not detected in any other neutral$/$singly-ionized metal transitions. The two other weak components at $v\sim-$40 and $-$25 {km~s$^{-1}$}\ are, however, present in the {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}}\ and {\mbox{Fe\,{\sc ii}}}\ absorption lines. The new COS observations cover several metal lines stemming from different elements (e.g., C, N, O, S, Si) and from different ionization states (e.g., {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}, {\mbox{C\,{\sc iii}}}, {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}). Except for the {\mbox{C\,{\sc i}}}\footnote{The red wing of the {\mbox{C\,{\sc i}}}~$\lambda$945 line is partially blended, possibly with the {Ly$\alpha$}\ absorption from {$z_{\rm abs}$}$=$0.1118 system.}, all other unblended neutral species (i.e., {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}\footnote{The {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}~$\lambda$988.7 line is self-blended with the weaker {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}~$\lambda$988.6 and $\lambda$988.5 lines}, {\mbox{N\,{\sc i}}}, and {\mbox{Ar\,{\sc i}}}) exhibit a single component, simple absorption kinematics. Except for the {\mbox{Si\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda$1020, {\mbox{P\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda$963, and {\mbox{N\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda$1083\footnote{We note that the {\mbox{N\,{\sc ii}}}\ line is partially blended with the Galactic {\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}}~$\lambda$1550 line.}, presence of multicomponent structure is seen in all other singly-ionized and higher ionization absorption lines\footnote{Note that the red-wing of the {\mbox{C\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda$1036 is contaminated with the L5R0 {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ line detected from this sub-DLA. Moreover, the {\mbox{N\,{\sc iii}}}~$\lambda$989 line is partly blebded with the {\mbox{Si\,{\sc ii}}}~$\lambda$989.8 absorption.}. Very strong, saturated {\mbox{C\,{\sc iii}}}\ absorption is detected over the entire velocity range for which other low ionization species, {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ in particular, are detected. 



The details of the high ionization species are presented in Appendix~\ref{sec:highion} since the main focus of this paper is the low ionization gas phase giving rise to {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ absorption. In brief, {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}~$\lambda\lambda$1031,1037 absorption lines are detected in both the doublets in the velocity range of $-100$ to $+200$~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ with a total line spread of $\Delta v_{90}=$~246 {km~s$^{-1}$}\ (see Figure~\ref{fig:highion}). No {\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}}\ and$/$or {\mbox{N\,{\sc v}}}\ lines are detected in this system. The Voigt profile fit parameters for the {\mbox{O\,{\sc vi}}}\ absorption and 3$\sigma$ upper limits on $N({\mbox{N\,{\sc v}}})$ and $N({\mbox{C\,{\sc iv}}})$ are given in Table~\ref{tab:highion}.      



Besides several metal absorption lines, numerous Lyman- and Werner-band absorption lines of {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}, arising from the $J=$ 0, 1, 2, and 3 rotational levels, are detected from this absorber. The {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ absorption lines that are not self-blended or contaminated by other unrelated absorption are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:H2fit}. Similar to neutral metal line transitions detected in the COS spectra, the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ lines from different $J$ levels also show a single component, simple absorption kinematics. Importantly, the absorption redshifts of {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ transitions coincide with the strongest metal line component.                          




\subsection{Absorption Line Measurements}    
\label{subsec:mea}  

We primarily use the {\sc vpfit}\footnote{http://www.ast.cam.ac.uk/$\sim$rfc/vpfit.html} software for measuring absorption line parameters (i.e., $N$, $b$, and $z$). Additionally, whenever possible, we have used the COG and the apparent optical depth (AOD) techniques. First we fit all the metal lines detected in the high resolution Keck spectrum simultaneously, i.e., by keeping the absorption redshift and $b$-parameter of a given component tied to each other. A minimum of five components are required to fit the {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ doublets satisfactorily. As noted earlier, the weak component at $v\sim+$90~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ is not present in any other lines detected in the Keck spectrum. Except for the component at $0$~{km~s$^{-1}$}, we tied the $b$-parameter of different ions via thermal broadening with a gas temperature of $10^{4}$~K. We note that a gas cloud photoionized by the extragalactic UV background radiation cannot cool efficiently below $10^{4}$~K via metal-line cooling \citep[]{Wiersma09}. Therefore, it is expected that the components without detected {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ will have gas temperatures on the order of or higher than $10^{4}$~K. For the strongest metal line component at $0$~{km~s$^{-1}$}, we set the temperature to be 156~K, i.e., the rotational excitation temperature ($T_{01}$) we obtain from the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ column densities in the $J=0$ and $J=1$ levels as discussed below. The Voigt profile fit parameters are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:fitHIRES} and the model profiles are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:fitHIRES}. Since there is no {Ly$\alpha$}\ forest crowding at low-$z$ and the absorption lines of interest do not fall on top of any emission line, the continuum fitting uncertainty is generally small and is not taken into account in the absorption line fit parameters. 



Next, we fit the sub-DLA profile detected in the medium resolution COS spectrum. Note that the line spread function (LSF) of the COS spectrograph is not a Gaussian. For our Voigt profile fit analysis we adopt the latest LSF given by \citet{Kriss11}. The LSF was obtained by interpolating the LSF tables at the observed central wavelength for each absorption line and was convolved with the model Voigt profile while fitting absorption lines using {\sc vpfit}. The total {\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}}\ column density we obtain by fitting the damping wing (Figure~\ref{fig:vplot}) of the {Ly$\alpha$}\ absorption is $N({\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}}) = 10^{19.50\pm0.15}$~{cm$^{-2}$}.    






Following \cite{Muzahid15a}, we choose a set of uncontaminated {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ lines for Voigt profile fitting (see Figure~\ref{fig:H2fit}). We fit them simultaneously by keeping the $b$-parameter tied. Additionally, we constrain the column density to be the same for all the transitions from a given $J$ level and allow it to be different for different $J$ levels. The COS wavelength calibration is known to have uncertainties at the level of 10--15~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ \citep[]{Savage11a}. We use the numerous {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ absorption lines as guide to improve the wavelength calibration uncertainty. Our final corrected spectrum has a velocity accuracy of $\sim\pm$5~{km~s$^{-1}$}. As a consequence, we did allow the redshift of individual transitions to be different from each other by a maximum of $\pm$5~{km~s$^{-1}$}.   



We noticed that depending upon the initial guess $b$-parameter, {\sc vpfit} converges at two different solutions with significantly different total $N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ values. The fit parameters are summarized in Table~\ref{tab:H2fit}. For a initial guess $b$ value of $\ge$8~{km~s$^{-1}$}, {\sc vpfit} converges with a $b({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ of 7.1$\pm$0.3 and a total $\log N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})=$~16.36$\pm$0.08. On the other hand, an initial guess $b$ value of $<$8~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ leads to a solution with a $b({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ of 2.8$\pm$0.3 and a total $\log N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})=$~18.27$\pm$0.03. Such a degeneracy is also present when we use the standard COG technique. The model profiles corresponding to the two different solutions are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:H2fit}. From the model profiles and$/$or from the reduced $\chi^2$ values, it is difficult to choose one model as opposed to the other. However, we note that the $b$-parameter in the latter case is significantly lower as compared to the velocity resolution of the COS spectra ($\sim$18~{km~s$^{-1}$}). Such a narrow $b$-value is not measured in the corresponding metal line component, even in the high resolution Keck data. Furthermore, we demonstrate in the next section that the observed $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}})$ to $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}})$ ratio does not allow $N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ to be as high as $10^{18.27}$~{cm$^{-2}$}. As such we exclude the higher $N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ solution.    




The unblended lines of {\mbox{N\,{\sc i}}}, {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}, {\mbox{Ar\,{\sc i}}}, and {\mbox{S\,{\sc ii}}}, detected in the COS spectra, are fitted with a single component Voigt profile keeping both redshift and $b$-parameter free (see Table~\ref{tab:fitCOS}). The weak {\mbox{Ar\,{\sc i}}}\ absorption is detected only in the $\lambda$1048 transition\footnote{The expected wavelength range for the other weaker transition of {\mbox{Ar\,{\sc i}}}\ (i.e., $\lambda$1066) is noisy and partly blended with the $\rm L3P2$ line of {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}.}. A free fit to the {\mbox{Ar\,{\sc i}}}~$\lambda$1048 leads to a highly erroneous solution. We, therefore, fix the $b$-parameter at 6.3~{km~s$^{-1}$}, which we obtained from the fit to the strongest metal line component detected in the Keck spectrum. The $b$-parameter of 16.8$\pm$4.0 {km~s$^{-1}$}\ required for a free fit to the weak {\mbox{S\,{\sc ii}}}\ absorption lines is higher than that is observed for the other lines. Nevertheless, the estimated column density is robust since the lines are weak and fall on the linear part of COG. Finally, due to the blend in the red wing of the {\mbox{C\,{\sc i}}}\ absorption, we estimate the maximum column density that can be accommodated by keeping the $b$-parameter and component velocity (i.e., {$z_{\rm abs}$}) the same as the {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}}\ line. We treat the $N({\mbox{C\,{\sc i}}})$ obtained by this method as a conservative upper limit.   





Next, we perform COG analysis for the ions detected in the medium resolution COS spectra with at least three available unblended transitions. The results of our COG analyses are shown in Figure~\ref{fig:COG}. The best fitting COG column densities and $b$-parameters are given in each panel of the figure. The $b$-parameters obtained for both {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}\ and {\mbox{N\,{\sc i}}}, using the COG method, are consistent with the $b$-parameter we measure for the strongest absorption component in the Keck spectrum. Moreover, they are also consistent with the values we obtain using {\sc vpfit} within 1$\sigma$ allowed uncertainties (see Table~\ref{tab:fitCOS}). The inferred $b$-parameter for {\mbox{Si\,{\sc ii}}}\ is somewhat higher than those for {\mbox{O\,{\sc i}}}\ and {\mbox{N\,{\sc i}}}. This is possibly due to the presence of multiple components in the strong {\mbox{Si\,{\sc ii}}}\ transitions. The $b$-parameter for {\mbox{S\,{\sc ii}}}\ is not well constrained since all three transitions are on the linear part of COG. It is interesting to note that at least one line in each case falls on the linear part of COG ensuring that the column densities we obtain using COG are robust.   






