Although the ionization model presented above is based on the observed total column densities, the dominating component is the one at $\sim$0~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ in which {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ is present. This component comprises about $\sim$60\% of the total {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ and {\mbox{Fe\,{\sc ii}}}, and $\sim$75\% of the total {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}}\ column densities. Thus the model parameters essentially correspond to this component. Due to the lack of $N({\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}})$ information in individual components we could not build component-by-component models. This is because all the higher order Lyman series lines are heavily saturated. Nonetheless, from the measured $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}})/N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}})$ and $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}})/N({\mbox{Fe\,{\sc ii}}})$ ratios we infer that the density in the two weak components at $v\sim-$30~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ (see Figure~\ref{fig:fitHIRES}) could be as high as seen in the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ component, provided the metallicities are not very low. The weakest {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ component at $v\sim$90~{km~s$^{-1}$}\ is more likely to be similar to the ``weak systems" studied by \cite{Rigby02}.  






