If we use the higher $N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ solution corresponding to $\log f_{{\mbox{\footnotesize H{$_2$}}}}=-$0.98 then the required density is $\log n_{\rm H} =$~0.8, i.e., an order of magnitude higher than our adopted density. At such a high density the $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}})/N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}})$ ratio is a factor of $\sim$5 higher than the observed value. Additionally, the predicted photoionization equilibrium temperature at this density (i.e. 40~K) is significantly lower than the corresponding $T_{01}$ value (143$\pm$17~K; see Table~\ref{tab:H2fit}). Next, \cite{Srianand12}  have found that {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ components in high-$z$ DLAs are compact (with sizes of $\lesssim$15~pc) and contain only a small fraction ($\lesssim$10\%) of the total $N({\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}})$. If this is also true for the present system then the {\mbox{H{$_2$}}}\ bearing gas would require a much higher density ($>10$~cm$^{-3}$) which is inconsistent with the density range allowed by the $N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc i}}})/N({\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}})$ ratio (see Figure~\ref{fig:model1}). Finally, we note that an appreciable stellar contribution to the ionizing background on top of the extra-galactic UV background would require a higher gas density in order to reproduce the same amount of $N({\mbox{H{$_2$}}})$ for a given $N({\mbox{H\,{\sc i}}})$ \citep[see e.g.][]{Muzahid15a,Dutta15}.                        





\section{Galaxy Analysis}  
\label{sec:galana}  

The $HST/$WFPC2 F702W image of the field is shown in the left column of Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}. The host-galaxy is located at an impact parameter of $\rho=$~48.4~kpc towards the north-east with respect to the QSO. The host-galaxy has an inclination angle of $i=48.3^{+3.5}_{-3.7}$~degree. The angle between the projected major-axis of the host-galaxy and the QSO sightline (i.e. the azimuthal angle, $\Phi$) is $14.9^{+0.6}_{-4.9}$~degree. The azimuthal angle indicates that the absorbing gas is located near to the projected major-axis. The $B-K$ color of 2.06 \cite[]{Kacprzak15}, suggests a moderate star-formation rate (SFR) in the host-galaxy. Due to the unavailability of flux calibrated spectra (see Section~\ref{sec:galdata}) we could not constrain the SFR of the host-galaxy. Nonetheless, the presence of H$\alpha$ and [{\mbox{N\,{\sc ii}}}] emission lines (see Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}), allowed us to measure a redshift of {$z_{\rm gal}$}~$=$~0.42966$\pm$0.00016 and a metallicity of $\rm 12+\log (O/H)=8.68\pm0.09$ for the host-galaxy. The metallicity is estimated using the $N2$ relation of \citet{Pettini04}, i.e.,  $\rm 12+\log (O/H)= 8.90+ 0.57\times N2$, where $N2\equiv$ {\mbox{N\,{\sc ii}}}$/\rm H\alpha$. We note that (i) the {$z_{\rm gal}$}\ is consistent with the {$z_{\rm abs}$}\ within 1$\sigma$ uncertainty and (ii) the host-galaxy has a metallicity consistent with the solar value \citep[i.e., $\rm 12+\log (O/H)=8.69$,][]{Asplund09}. 



The point spread function (PSF) subtracted and magnified image of the QSO field is shown in the middle column of Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}. Interestingly, we found another galaxy at a much lower impact parameter ($\rho=2.06''$) in this image. In fact, the presence of this dwarf galaxy is noticeable even in the left column of Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}. This galaxy could be a satellite of the bigger galaxy at $\rho=$~48.4~kpc. However, we do not have a spectrum of this galaxy to constrain its redshift. Assuming that the dwarf galaxy is at {$z_{\rm abs}$}, we obtain an impact parameter of $\rho =11.6$~kpc and an apparent magnitude of $m_{\rm F702W}=23.20\pm0.06$ (Vega). The dwarf-satellite galaxy is highly inclined with $i=70.0^{+15.0}_{-21.1}$~degree. Similar to the bigger galaxy, the projected major-axis of the satellite galaxy also has a small azimuthal angle, i.e., $\Phi=10.6^{+19.4}_{-10.6}$~degree, with respect to the QSO sightline.      



The rotation curve of the spectroscopically confirmed host-galaxy is constructed using the [{\mbox{O\,{\sc iii}}}]~$\lambda$5008 emission line and is shown in the right column of Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}. The zero velocity here corresponds to the {$z_{\rm gal}$}\ and not to {$z_{\rm abs}$}. The galaxy has a maximum projected rotation velocity of $|v_{\rm max}|\sim$170~{km~s$^{-1}$}. Note that the rotation curve at the $-ve$ velocities is affected by a sky-line contamination to the [{\mbox{O\,{\sc iii}}}]~$\lambda$5008 line. 



We now construct the halo model of \cite{Steidel02} using $i$, $\Phi$, $\rho$, and $v_{\rm max}$ of the host-galaxy. Following \cite{Kacprzak10a} we use the gas scale height, $h_{v}$, a free parameter of the model, to be 1000~kpc (for a non lagging halo above the galaxy plane). Such a model examines the range of allowed velocities along the line of sight that are consistent with extended galaxy rotation. The model is shown in the bottom panel of the right column of Figure~\ref{fig:HSTimage}. The $D_{\rm los}$ is the distance along the line of sight relative to the point where the sightline intercepts the projected mid-plane of the galaxy. A halo model is considered successful when the $D_{\rm los}$ curve spans the same velocity range as that of the observed {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ absorption. It is important to notice that the observed {\mbox{Mg\,{\sc ii}}}\ kinematics is {\it not} consistent with such a model of a co-rotating disk but is consistent with a counter-rotating lagging halo.          






